    pearls: ["The Beers Criteria (updated by AGS) identifies potentially inappropriate medications in older adults — memorize the high-risk categories: anticholinergics, benzodiazepines, NSAIDs, and first-generation antihistamines","The prescribing cascade is a common driver of polypharmacy: Drug A causes side effect → side effect mistaken for new condition → Drug B prescribed → Drug B causes side effect → Drug C prescribed","NEVER abruptly stop benzodiazepines, beta-blockers, SSRIs, PPIs, or corticosteroids — all have withdrawal syndromes requiring gradual tapering","Deprescribe one medication at a time to clearly attribute any withdrawal symptoms or disease recurrence to the specific medication change","Question all medications without a clear current indication — the indication that prompted the prescription may have resolved, or the patient's goals may have changed","In patients with limited life expectancy, preventive medications (statins, bisphosphonates, aspirin for primary prevention) may no longer provide benefit and should be considered for deprescribing"],
